  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. Here are some key details:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences up to 20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in the transaction\n\n2. Specific Statutory Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering criminal offenses\n- Penalties vary based on specific circumstances of the crime\n\n3. Factors Influencing Sentencing:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Purpose of the transaction\n- Involvement in other criminal activities\n- Prior criminal history\n\n4. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\n5. Federal Agencies Involved:\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n\nPlease note that actual penalties depend on specific case details and judicial discretion. For precise legal advice about a specific situation, consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney is recommended.",
